<font color="#FF0000">UNNECESSARY DEATHS.</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec  1  2:19:02 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
So many young men served their country during this war, without even really knowing why.  Those who did not ask to go there but did so without protest, answering the call of their government.  They TRULY risked their life daily for a year or more, hardly ever giving it a thought; most did what they were supposed to do, and went on to the next day!  Some of us did this, only to find out that politics and booming industries back home, and their CEO's and friends, just had us all there, to the extent of giving our life, so their economics could continue to boom: THAT GREAT MILITARY MACHINE; that great money producing machine.  <br>
     I will of course die wondering why, on May 1st of 1970,  while in Phan Thiet, the highly unusual order was given for everyone to turn-in every weapon into the armory.  Rumors had been floating around just prior to that time that we were going to get &quot;hit&quot;.  THAT NIGHT, at 11:35 pm, we were!  I happened to have guard duty that night, at bunker #14, with Miller and some other guy whose name I now don't recall.  For that, we were allowed to sign-out ONE M-79, which we had to share amongst the three of us.  You can't imagine the scramble when Charlie hit.  They came under the wire, got in, burned some BRAND NEW helicopters which had just &quot;happened&quot; to have been brought in earlier that day, killed at random, and left.  Almost everyone was still trying to get ahold of ANY weapon.  <br>
     Was all this just a coincidence?  Was it Charlie taking advantage of the opportunity, having seen that we had all, for some reason, disarmed ourselves that day?  I DON'T THINK  SO, AND I WILL NEVER THINK SO!  We were ALL set up.  Someone(s) in Washington needed casualties in Vietnam that day, and we were to be those casualties.  Did someone here need to show why they truly needed more appropriations to build more weapons and equipment, send more men to Vietnam and, thus, have to buy more uniforms and boots from someone's factory here?  Or was it that someone needed to show more casualties in Vietnam to enforce the idea of retreat by the U.S. from that war?  <br>
     I will die not knowing the answers to &quot;why&quot;, but I'll go knowing that I, and those who died that night there, were betrayed by our own government; more specifically,(being that &quot;government&quot; is really an abstract),  by some of the HUMAN members of government who so eloquently speak one thing, even cry, and then do another for their own personal gain.  <br>
     How did the Vietnam war change me?  I'm not sure that the war itself changed me negatively at all; that great, politician / army-high-brass structure did!  It destroyed the blind loyalty I had towards this nation.  I did not die there that night and first morning hour of May 2nd, 1970; I spent over a year there and did what I was supposed to, pretty much without objection, and anxiously awaited to come back home.  I was betrayed by MEN in government, and I will die KNOWING that.  I'm only sorry that so many others who were also betrayed had to die because of it.  
